\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Each layer of this sonification used a combination of a musical inverse spectrogram and discrete parameter mapping for compact sources. Each image row was assigned a unique musical pitch (with increasing frequency towards the top of the image); and we used the brightness of the diffuse nebula to control the volume of pure sustained tones. Discrete bright sources (mainly stars) were mapped to individual notes using the same height-frequency mapping. The sonification utilized different instruments depending on the wavelength of light depicted: a glockenspiel for Chandra\'92s X-ray light, a plucked string for Hubble\'92s optical light, and a piano for Spitzer\'92s infrared light.\'a0
